⚛.description: Atom Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🕉.name: Om
🕉.description: A symbol often used in relation to the religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism. Om was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Om Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

✡.name: Star of David
✡.description: A symbol often used in relation to the religion of Judaism. Not to be confused with the Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot emoji. Star of David was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

☸.name: Wheel of Dharma
☸.description: A symbol often used in relation to the Indian religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism. Wheel of Dharma was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

☯.name: Yin Yang
☯.description: Yin Yang was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

✝.name: Latin Cross
✝.description: A latin cross, otherwise known as a Christian cross. This cross symbol is often used as a symbol of Christianity. Similar in appearance to the Orthodox cross. Latin Cross was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

☦.name: Orthodox Cross
☦.description: Orthodox Cross was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

☪.name: Star and Crescent
☪.description: The crescent moon and star is a symbol often associated with the religion of Islam. This symbol can be found on the flags of many countries, such as Algeria, Azerbaijan, Malaysia, Pakistan and Turkey. Star and Crescent was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993  and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

☮.name: Peace Symbol
☮.description: A circular symbol, commonly used as a representation of peace. Alternatives include the Victory Hand, or the Dove of Peace. Peace Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🕎.name: Menorah
🕎.description: A menorah showing nine lit candles, used on the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah. Menorah was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 under the name “Menorah with Nine Branches” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔯.name: Dotted Six-Pointed Star
🔯.description: A star with six points, and a dot in the center. Similar to the Star of David emoji. Dotted Six-Pointed Star was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Six Pointed Star with Middle Dot” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♈.name: Aries
♈.description: The Aries astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Ram. Aries was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♉.name: Taurus
♉.description: The Taurus astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Bull. Taurus was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♊.name: Gemini
♊.description: The Gemini astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents Twins. Gemini was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♋.name: Cancer
♋.description: The Cancer astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Crab. Cancer was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♌.name: Leo
♌.description: The Leo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Lion. Leo was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♍.name: Virgo
♍.description: The Virgo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Maiden. Virgo was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♎.name: Libra
♎.description: The Libra astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents weighing scales. Libra was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♏.name: Scorpio
♏.description: The Scorpius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Scorpion. Scorpio was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Scorpius” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♐.name: Sagittarius
♐.description: The Sagittarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents an Archer. Sagittarius was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♑.name: Capricorn
♑.description: The Capricorn astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Goat. Capricorn was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♒.name: Aquarius
♒.description: The Aquarius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Water-bearer. Aquarius was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♓.name: Pisces
♓.description: The Pisces astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Fish. Pisces was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⛎.name: Ophiuchus
⛎.description: Ophiuchus is used by some as a 13th sign in the Zodiac. The symbol for ophiuchus appears a U shape with a wavy line through it. Ophiuchus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔀.name: Shuffle Tracks Button
🔀.description: Two arrows pointing right while crossing over one another. Used to indicate putting music on shuffle: randomizing the order of tracks in the upcoming playlist. May also be used to indicate two items switching places. Shuffle Tracks Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Twisted Rightwards Arrows” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔁.name: Repeat Button
🔁.description: Circular arrows pointing in a clockwise direction. Used in music player applications to loop a track or album continuously. Commonly used to repesent a retweet on Twitter. Repeat Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔂.name: Repeat Single Button
🔂.description: Arrows pointing in a clockwise direction, with a number 1 badge in the lower corner.  Used in music player applications to loop a track or album once. Repeat Single Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows with Circled One Overlay” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy
🔂.aliases:
🔂 Circle Arrows With Number 1
🔂 Loop Once Symbol

▶.name: Play Button
▶.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing right. Commonly used as a symbol for play. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Play Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏩.name: Fast-Forward Button
⏩.description: Two triangles pointing to the right. Most commonly used as a symbol for fast forwarding media such as video tapes, CDs, or digital audio and video. Fast-Forward Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.   Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏭.name: Next Track Button
⏭.description: A symbol used in media players to indicate skipping to the next track  or scene . Shown as two triangles pointing right followed by a vertical bar. Next Track Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle with Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.   Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏯.name: Play or Pause Button
⏯.description: A play-pause icon, showing a right-pointing triangle  play  next to a double vertical bar  pause . Play or Pause Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Triangle with Double Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

◀.name: Reverse Button
◀.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing left. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Reverse Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Black Left-Pointing Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏪.name: Fast Reverse Button
⏪.description: Two triangles pointing to the left. Most commonly used as a symbol for rewinding media such as video tapes, CDs, or digital audio and video. Fast Reverse Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Left-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏮.name: Last Track Button
⏮.description: A symbol used in media players to indicate skipping to the first or previous track  or scene . Shown as a vertical bar followed by two triangles pointing left. Last Track Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Left-Pointing Double Triangle with Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔼.name: Upwards Button
🔼.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing up. Styled similarly to the left and right pointing triangles on iOS, but shown in red on Windows, and orange on Android. Upwards Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Up-Pointing Small Red Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏫.name: Fast Up Button
⏫.description: Two triangles pointing up. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° clockwise. Fast Up Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Up-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔽.name: Downwards Button
🔽.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing down. Styled similarly to the left and right pointing triangles on iOS, but shown in red on Windows, and orange on Android. Downwards Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Down-Pointing Small Red Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏬.name: Fast Down Button
⏬.description: Two triangles pointing down. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° counter-clockwise. Fast Down Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Down-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏸.name: Pause Button
⏸.description: A pause icon, displayed as two vertical bars. Pause Button was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Double Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏹.name: Stop Button
⏹.description: A stop icon, displayed as a square. Stop Button was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Black Square for Stop” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏺.name: Record Button
⏺.description: A record icon, displayed as a circle. Record Button was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Black Circle for Record” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⏏.name: Eject Button
⏏.description: An eject symbol, displayed as an upward-pointing triangle above a horiztonal bar. May be used as a physical button or an icon in a user interface. Represents the action of ejecting physical media such as a floppy disk, videocasette or DVD on a computer or media player. Eject Button was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 under the name “Eject Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🎦.name: Cinema
🎦.description: An emoji representing the cinema: a large screen showing the latest movies, available to the public. Displayed by most platforms as a film projector symbol, and previously by Google and Microsoft as a cinema screen with curtains. Cinema was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔅.name: Dim Button
🔅.description: An icon of a outlined sun, used when decreasing the brightness of a screen. Appears smaller than the High Brightness Symbol. Dim Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Low Brightness Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔆.name: Bright Button
🔆.description: An icon of a outlined sun, used when increasing the brightness of a screen. Appears larger than the Low Brightness Symbol. Bright Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “High Brightness Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

📶.name: Antenna Bars
📶.description: Bars increasing in height, showing the strength of the mobile  cellular  phone signal. More bars signifies better reception. Antenna Bars was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Antenna with Bars” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

📳.name: Vibration Mode
📳.description: An icon representing vibration mode on a mobile phone, indicating that a phone should be switched to silent and/or vibrate mode. Displayed as a phone with either zig-zag lines or muted-bell icon on most platforms. Early versions of this emoji often used a heart alongside a mobile phone, as commonly seen in Japan. Vibration Mode was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

📴.name: Mobile Phone Off
📴.description: A sign indicating that mobile phones should be turned off. Used in situations such as a cinema or live performance. Displayed as a mobile phone with the word OFF. Shown with a cross instead of the word OFF on Windows. Mobile Phone Off was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♀.name: Female Sign
♀.description: A circle shown with a crossed vertical line beneath it, used as a representation for women. Female Sign was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♂.name: Male Sign
♂.description: A circle shown with a diagonal arrow pointing out the top-right, used as a representation for men. Male Sign was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

✖.name: Multiply
✖.description: Multiply was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Heavy Multiplication X” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

➕.name: Plus
➕.description: Plus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Heavy Plus Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

➖.name: Minus
➖.description: Minus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Heavy Minus Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

➗.name: Divide
➗.description: Divide was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Heavy Division Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♾.name: Infinity
♾.description: The symbol for infinity enclosed within a circle or square. Originally encoded as a symbol to represent acid-free paper, this permanent paper sign was later given emoji presentation to form an infinity emoji. Infinity was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 under the name “Permanent Paper Sign” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

‼.name: Double Exclamation Mark
‼.description: Double Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⁉.name: Exclamation Question Mark
⁉.description: Exclamation Question Mark was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

❓.name: Question Mark
❓.description: Question Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Question Mark Ornament” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

❔.name: White Question Mark
❔.description: White Question Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “White Question Mark Ornament” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

❕.name: White Exclamation Mark
❕.description: White Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “White Exclamation Mark Ornament” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

❗.name: Exclamation Mark
❗.description: Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name “Heavy Exclamation Mark Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

〰.name: Wavy Dash
〰.description: Just like a regular dash  hyphen , sometimes used in Asian character sets in the same way a – or — is used in latin character sets. Wavy Dash was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

💱.name: Currency Exchange
💱.description: A symbol for exchanging of two currencies. Most commonly displayed as a dollar symbol, with arrows to and from a yen symbol. Some platforms instead show banknotes and coins in yen, dollars, euros and pounds.  Currency Exchange was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

💲.name: Heavy Dollar Sign
💲.description: Heavy Dollar Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⚕.name: Medical Symbol
⚕.description: A symbol displaying of a rod with a snake entwined around the outside in a downward-spiral shape. Associated with medicine and health care services such as doctors or hospitals. A similar and related symbol called the Caduceus is frequently used in the United States. Medical Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 under the name “Staff of Aesculapius” and added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

♻.name: Recycling Symbol
♻.description: The universal recycling symbol, featuring three arrows pointing clockwise in a triangular formation. The word “black” in the official name is due to this emoji existing as a unicode character before the current standardized emoji set. Recycling Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 under the name “Black Universal Recycling Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⚜.name: Fleur-de-lis
⚜.description: A decorative symbol that appears like a golden flower, but found in all manner of logos, symbols, and patterns. This symbol forms part of the World Scout Emblem, amongst other uses. Fleur-de-lis was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🔱.name: Trident Emblem
🔱.description: A trident is a three-pronged spear, that appears similar to a pitchfork. Often held by Greek or Roman Gods in statues. Trident Emblem was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

📛.name: Name Badge
📛.description: A name badge, used to identify oneself in a location that others may not know your name, such as a school trip, or a work conference. This tulip-shaped name badge is one of many designs commonly found at kindergartens in Japan. Name Badge was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy
📛.aliases:
📛 Fire Tag
📛 Name Tag
📛 Tofu On Fire

🔰.name: Japanese Symbol for Beginner
🔰.description: A yellow and green shield symbol, called a Shoshinsha Mark. Must be displayed by drivers in Japan for one year after they receive their drivers licence. Similar to L-Plates used to identify learner drivers in other countries. Japanese Symbol for Beginner was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⭕.name: Hollow Red Circle
⭕.description: Used as an alternative to a check  tick  in Japan for a something that is correct. The opposite of an X  cross mark  for something wrong. Hollow Red Circle was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name “Heavy Large Circle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

✅.name: Check Mark Button
✅.description: A check mark that displays with a white outlined appearance. Shows on most platforms with a bright green rounded rectangle or circle surrounding it. Android previously displayed this as an outlined blue check mark / blue tick. This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Check Mark Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010  under the name “White Heavy Check Mark” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

☑.name: Check Box with Check
☑.description: A checkbox showing a check mark inside the box. Not to be confused with the similarly named Ballot Box With Ballot emoji. This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Check Box with Check was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Ballot Box with Check” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

✔.name: Check Mark
✔.description: A thick  heavy  check mark displayed on some platforms in a handwritten style. Generally displayed in black on most platforms, except Android  blue , Windows  green  and Samsung  red . This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Check Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Heavy Check Mark” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

❌.name: Cross Mark
❌.description: A large red cross mark, displayed in the shape of a letter X and similar to a multiplication sign. Cross Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

❎.name: Cross Mark Button
❎.description: Cross Mark Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Negative Squared Cross Mark” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

➰.name: Curly Loop
➰.description: A curled loop, which is shown in black on most platforms. Displayed as a blue ribbon on Samsung devices. Similar to the Double Curly Loop but with only a single loop. Curly Loop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

➿.name: Double Curly Loop
➿.description: Two curly loops, which represent a reel-to-reel tape recorder. Used as a symbol for voicemail on many phones. A variation of this logo is used by Free Dial, a toll-free telephone number by NTT in Japan. Double Curly Loop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

〽.name: Part Alternation Mark
〽.description: Used in traditional Japanese music such as Noh or Renga, to indicate the start of a song. More specifically, the part alternation mark is displayed where the singer’s part begins. This symbol looks sort of like a lopsided capital M; or a rollercoaster track showing a dip, and then a drop off to the right. Part Alternation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

✳.name: Eight-Spoked Asterisk
✳.description: Used in a similar manner to a regular * asterisk character but tends to be shown in a similar vertical alignment to a • bullet point. The eight spoked asterisk has both a ✳︎ text and ✳️ emoji presentation available on most platforms. Eight-Spoked Asterisk was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Eight Spoked Asterisk” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

✴.name: Eight-Pointed Star
✴.description: A star with eight points, that is commonly shown in orange, and for some reason, with only four points. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Eight-Pointed Star was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Eight Pointed Black Star” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

❇.name: Sparkle
❇.description: Used a decorative bullet-point, the sparkle has both a ❇︎ text and ❇️ emoji presentation available on most platforms. Sparkle was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

©.name: Copyright
©.description: Copyright was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Copyright Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

®.name: Registered
®.description: Registered was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Registered Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

™.name: Trade Mark
™.description: A trademark symbol, the letters TM displayed after a word that is trademarked. Trade Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Trade Mark Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

#️⃣.name: Keycap Number Sign
#️⃣.description: A hash key, sometimes referred to as a pound key in the United States. Most commonly used online to make a hashtag  or hash flag  on social media sites. The Keycap Number Sign emoji is a keycap sequence combining # Number Sign and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Keycap Number Sign was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy
#️⃣.aliases:
#️⃣ Hash Key
#️⃣ Hashtag
#️⃣ Octothorpe
#️⃣ Pound Key

*️⃣.name: Keycap Asterisk
*️⃣.description: The Keycap Asterisk emoji is a keycap sequence combining * Asterisk and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Keycap Asterisk was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

0️⃣.name: Keycap Digit Zero
0️⃣.description: The Keycap Digit Zero emoji is a keycap sequence combining 0 Digit Zero and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Keycap Digit Zero was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

1️⃣.name: Keycap Digit One
1️⃣.description: The Keycap Digit One emoji is a keycap sequence combining 1 Digit One and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Keycap Digit One was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

2️⃣.name: Keycap Digit Two
2️⃣.description: The Keycap Digit Two emoji is a keycap sequence combining 2 Digit Two and ⃣ Combining Enclosing Keycap. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. 🧗.name: Person Climbing
🧗.description: A rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet and/or rope. The Emojipedia Sample image was created with assistance from World Champion Rock Climber Sasha DiGiulian. Variations exist for 🧗‍♀️ Woman Climbing and 🧗‍♂️ Man Climbing. Person Climbing was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 Previously displayed a gendered appearance; most platforms switched to a gender-inclusive design for this emoji in 2019.

🧗\u200d♂️.name: Man Climbing
🧗\u200d♂️.description: A male rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope. Variations exist for 🧗‍♀️ Woman Climbing and 🧗 Person Climbing. The Man Climbing emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🧗 Person Climbing, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♂ Male Sign. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms.  Man Climbing was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🧗\u200d♀️.name: Woman Climbing
🧗\u200d♀️.description: A female rock climber, shown climbing up a rock formation. Some platforms show the climber with a helmet, and/or rope. Variations exist for 🧗‍♂️ Man Climbing and 🧗 Person Climbing. The Woman Climbing emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🧗 Person Climbing, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ♀ Female Sign. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Woman Climbing was added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🤺.name: Person Fencing

🏇.name: Horse Racing
🏇.description: A jockey riding a horse in a horse race. Shown riding to the left of screen on all major platforms. Emoji modifiers change the skin tone of the jockey on some platforms, which can be difficult to discern at small sizes. Horse Racing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

⛷.name: Skier
⛷.description: A person downhill-skiiing. Displayed with poles and skis, generally wearing a mask. Platforms vary in display of scarf, helmet, and color of clothing. No gendered options are provided for this emoji. Skin tones support is not recommended for this emoji, but this is supported by some platforms. 🥦.description: A rich green, tree-like head or floret of broccoli.  Broccoli was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🧄.name: Garlic
🧄.description: Garlic was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🧅.name: Onion
🧅.description: Onion was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🥜.name: Peanuts
🥜.description: The pod of the peanut, shown in its rounded, grooved, light-brown shell. Apple depicts a pair. May be used for peanut butter as well as other edible nuts  e.g., almonds  or metaphorical ones, including slang for “crazy” and “testicle.” Peanuts was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍞.name: Bread
🍞.description: A loaf of white or wheat bread, as before it is sliced for toast or sandwiches. Bread was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥐.name: Croissant
🥐.description: The flaky, golden-brown crescent of a croissant, a breakfast pastry associated with France and Austria. Croissant was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥖.name: Baguette Bread
🥖.description: The long, thin loaf of a baguette, with scoring on its golden-brown crust. A bread commonly associated with France. Baguette Bread was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥨.name: Pretzel
🥨.description: The heart-shaped twist of a hard or soft golden-brown pretzel, seasoned with grains of salt. A snack commonly associated with Germany. Pretzel was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥯.name: Bagel
🥯.description: The brown bread of a bagel, shown sliced in two halves. Some platforms depict seeds, as sesame or poppy, and a schmear of cream cheese, with the bagel assembled as a sandwich. May resemble the Doughnut at small sizes. After complaints, Apple updated the bagel emoji design during the iOS 12.1 beta cycle. Bagel was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥞.name: Pancakes
🥞.description: A stack of breakfast pancakes, topped with a pad of butter and maple syrup oozing down its golden-brown sides, onto a plate on some platforms. Associated with the Christian observance of Shrove Tuesday, or "Pancake Day." Pancakes was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🧇.name: Waffle
🧇.description: Waffle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🧀.name: Cheese Wedge
🧀.description: A wedge of yellow-orange cheese with holes, like a Swiss, but used for the food in general. May be used for various cheese-related slang expressions  e.g., “cheesy,” “say cheese,” “big cheese” . Cheese Wedge was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍖.name: Meat on Bone
🍖.description: A hunk of unspecified meat on a white bone, as associated with cartoon cavepersons or food in anime and manga  Japanese ano niku, “that meat” . This emoji was shown as a steak in Android 4.4. Meat on Bone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍗.name: Poultry Leg
🍗.description: A crispy brown leg  drumstick  of chicken, duck, turkey, or other poultry on the bone, as roasted at Thanksgiving or Christmas dinner or fried at fast-food restaurants. Poultry Leg was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥩.name: Cut of Meat
🥩.description: A cut of uncooked red meat, as a T-bone or rib-eye steak, with the light, white marbling of fat. May be used for sexual slang. Cut of Meat was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥓.name: Bacon
🥓.description: Strips of crispy, fatty, reddish-brown bacon, as fried for breakfast. Depicted as a pair on most platforms. Bacon was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍔.name: Hamburger
🍔.description: A burger with a beef patty, usually depicted on a sesame bun with cheese, lettuce, and tomato—making it a cheeseburger, though officially called Hamburger by Unicode. Platforms stack the ingredients in various orders. Google previously placed the cheese under the patty, a "controversy" CEO Sundar Pichai addressed in 2018.  Hamburger was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍟.name: French Fries
🍟.description: Thin-cut, golden-brown French fries, served in a red carton, as at McDonald’s. Apple features Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes on its carton. French Fries was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍕.name: Pizza
🍕.description: A slice of pepperoni pizza, topped with black olives on Google. WhatsApp adds green pepper, Samsung white onion. Pizza was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Slice of Pizza” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🌭.name: Hot Dog
🌭.description: The cooked sausage of a hot dog in a sliced bun and drizzled with yellow mustard, as eaten at a baseball game.  Hot Dog was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥪.name: Sandwich
🥪.description: A sandwich, as eaten at lunch, made with lettuce, tomato, and cheese on slices of white or wheat bread. Apple, Google, and WhatsApp add a deli meat that resembles ham. Sandwich was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🌮.name: Taco
🌮.description: A Mexican or Tex-Mex taco on a hard or soft corn tortilla, filled with such ingredients as beef, lettuce, tomato, cheese, and onion. Apple’s design resembles a carne asada taco, with cilantro and white onion. Taco was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🌯.name: Burrito
🌯.description: A Mexican or Tex-Mex burrito, featuring a wrapped flour tortilla filled with such ingredients as beef, rice, beans, cheese, tomato, lettuce, and sour cream. Served in foil on several major platforms, suggesting a Mission burrito associated with San Francisco. Not to be confused with the Stuffed Flatbread. Burrito was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015  and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥙.name: Stuffed Flatbread
🥙.description: A flatbread, like pita, stuffed with lettuce, tomato, and/or meat. Resembles a doner kebab, falafel, shawarma, or gyro sandwich, popular in the Middle East and the Mediterranean. Apple and WhatsApp add red onion and cucumber. Not to be confused with the Burrito. Stuffed Flatbread was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🧆.name: Falafel
🧆.description: Falafel was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🥚.name: Egg
🥚.description: An egg, displayed as a chicken egg with a white or light brown shell. Commonly used at Easter time. See also: 🍳 Cooking. Egg was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍳.name: Cooking
🍳.description: An egg with yolk frying in a skillet, as prepared sunny-side up. Though associated with breakfast, the emoji represents the general action of cooking and related concepts. Cooking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥘.name: Shallow Pan of Food
🥘.description: A flat, shallow, black pan with side handles, containing saffron-colored rice, vegetables, a leg of poultry, and/or shrimp and lemon slices. Commonly associated with paella, a traditional dish from Spain. May be used for eating, cooking, dining, and meals more generally. Apple's version of this emoji is considered to be representative of the traditional ingredients from Valencia. Samsung previously displayed this emoji as a Korean hot pot. Shallow Pan of Food was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍲.name: Pot of Food
🍲.description: A pot, as a casserole dish, filled with a warm and hearty beef or vegetable stew on most platforms. Samsung’s design resembles a bowl of ramen or other noodle dish, with chopsticks. Generally used for eating and cooking  “a meal” , and commonly associated with soup or Japanese nabe. Pot of Food was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.   Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥣.name: Bowl with Spoon
🥣.description: A bowl with a silver spoon inside, as used to eat cereal or soup. Bowl color varies across platforms, as do contents. Android depicts breakfast cereal, WhatsApp tomato soup; Apple’s is empty. Bowl with Spoon was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥗.name: Green Salad
🥗.description: An undressed garden salad in a bowl with leafy-green lettuce and other ingredients such as tomato, red onion, and black olives. Commonly associated with healthy eating and living. Google previously displayed a hard-boiled egg, removed in 2018 to make the salad vegan-friendly. Green Salad was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍿.name: Popcorn
🍿.description: The buttery-white snack of popcorn brimming in a classic red-and-white-striped carton, as enjoyed at a movie theater.  May be used to express engagement  “edge of one’s seat” . Popcorn was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🧈.name: Butter
🧈.description: Butter was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🧂.name: Salt
🧂.description: A clear glass shaker of salt with a silver cap, as paired with pepper to season food when eating at a restaurant. Salt was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “Salt Shaker” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥫.name: Canned Food
🥫.description: A can or tin of food, depicted as tomatoes or a generic green vegetable. May be also used to represent sauce or soup. Canned Food was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy
🥫.aliases:
🥫 Can of Food
🥫 Tin Can
🥫 Tinned Food

🍱.name: Bento Box
🍱.description: A Japanese bento, a lunch box divided into portions of rice, vegetables, and meat or seafood, such as sushi or fried shrimp. Bento Box was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍘.name: Rice Cracker
🍘.description: A Japanese senbei, or rice cracker, wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed, a snack commonly enjoyed with green tea. Rice Cracker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍙.name: Rice Ball
🍙.description: A Japanese onigiri, a cone-shaped ball of white rice, a snack wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed. Rice Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍚.name: Cooked Rice
🍚.description: A bowl of steamed white rice, a staple component of cuisine throughout Asia. Bowl color varies across platforms, though is often white. Cooked Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy
🍚.aliases:
🍚 Boiled Rice
🍚 Bowl Of Rice
🍚 Rice
🍚 Steamed Rice

🍛.name: Curry Rice
🍛.description: A plate of orange-brown curry with vegetables or meat, served with a mound of white rice. May represent kare-raisu, or Japanese curry, though commonly associated with India and other Asian cuisines. Curry Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Curry and Rice” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍜.name: Steaming Bowl
🍜.description: A bowl of steaming-hot food. Depicted as Japanese ramen  noodles in broth  with chopsticks on most platforms, though it can represent a warm meal more generally. Samsung’s design resembles Pot of Food. Steaming Bowl was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍝.name: Spaghetti
🍝.description: A plate of Italian spaghetti with tomato sauce, as a bolognese, with a fork twirling its long, thin noodles. Garnished with a green herb, as parsley, on some platforms. Spaghetti was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍠.name: Roasted Sweet Potato
🍠.description: A sweet potato depicted with textured purple, orange, or brown skin and sliced in half to show its golden-brown flesh. Sometimes called a yam, though they are unrelated. Not to be confused with the Potato. Commonly roasted as a snack in East Asia during winter, much as squash and pumpkin are popular in the United States during fall/autumn. Used as an offering to the full moon in Japan during the Moon Viewing harvest festival. Roasted Sweet Potato was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍢.name: Oden
🍢.description: A skewer of three bites of Japanese oden, a winter dish made with fishcakes, tofu, konnyaku, and a variety of other ingredients, including boiled eggs. Often served as a stew or skewered and dipped into soy sauce. Resembles the Dango and may be used for other skewered foods  e.g., shish kebab, roasting marshmallows  or spears. Oden was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍣.name: Sushi
🍣.description: Japanese sushi, generally depicted as two pieces of raw pinkish-orange fish, as tuna or salmon, on white rice  nigiri . Some platforms show the cylindrical maki, a piece of seafood, vegetables, and white rice wrapped in seaweed  nori . Sushi was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍤.name: Fried Shrimp
🍤.description: A prawn or shrimp breaded and deep-fried golden-brown. Known as ebi furai in Japan but commonly called shrimp tempura and served in a bento box. Not to be confused with the Shrimp. Fried Shrimp was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.  Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍥.name: Fish Cake with Swirl
🍥.description: A slice of Japanese narutomaki, a ridged fishcake of processed whitefish with an iconic pink swirl, often served in ramen or oden. Thanks to its distinct swirl, may be used for flair. Fish Cake with Swirl was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Fish Cake with Swirl Design” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥮.name: Moon Cake
🥮.description: The round, golden-brown pastry of a Chinese mooncake, a traditional delicacy and lunar symbol of the Mid-Autumn Festival. Many platforms feature a design or character imprinted on the crust, and depict a slice cut out to show a brown paste with a duck egg yolk inside. Twitter displays the Chinese character for “fall/autumn” or “harvest”  秋  on top. Moon Cake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍡.name: Dango
🍡.description: A Japanese sweet dumpling made from rice flour and served on a skewer. Depicted as a botchan dango, comprising a pink, white or light yellow, and green ball, as colored by red beans, egg, and green tea. Resembles the Oden and featured in the Moon Viewing Ceremony, used in the Japanese festival to celebrate the full moon.  Dango was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy
🍡.aliases:
🍡 Dessert Stick
🍡 Pink White Green Balls

🥟.name: Dumpling
🥟.description: A dumpling of dough and filling, as folded and pinched closed for steaming or frying. Associated with cuisines around the world, including China  jiaozi , Japan  gyoza or dango , Poland  pierogi , and Spain and Latin America  empanada . Facebook's design resembles a xiaolongbao, a Chinese soup dumpling. Dumpling was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥠.name: Fortune Cookie
🥠.description: A golden-brown, crescent-shaped, vanilla-flavored fortune cookie. Usually depicted with a strip of paper—on which a wise saying, lucky numbers, or Chinese vocabulary is written—peaking out of its hollow shell. Given at the end of meals at Chinese restaurants in the West. Fortune Cookie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥡.name: Takeout Box
🥡.description: A tall, folded, paper carton, usually white, as used for takeout/takeaway food at Western Chinese restaurants. Most platforms depict chopsticks inside its open lid, labeled with a red, multi-tiered, traditional Chinese building. Also called an oyster pail. Takeout Box was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🦪.name: Oyster
🦪.description: An oyster, a mollusk used for food or pearls. Depicted as half of an opened oyster with a pinkish body in a rough, brown-and-white shell, bearing a pearl on many platforms. Oyster was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🍦.name: Soft Ice Cream
🍦.description: A swirl of soft-serve ice cream atop a wafer-style cone, white or cream-colored, as vanilla, on most platforms. Facebook’s design suggests strawberry. May be used more generally for ice cream, frozen yogurt, and frozen treats. Soft Ice Cream was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍧.name: Shaved Ice
🍧.description: A mound of shaved ice  snow cone  served in a dessert bowl with a short spoon, flavored with a cherry-red syrup on many platforms. Associated with Hawaiian shave ice or Japanese kakigori. Shaved Ice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍨.name: Ice Cream
🍨.description: One or more scoops of ice cream in a dessert bowl, variously topped with sprinkles, wafer rolls, or cherry and syrup. Flavors vary from vanilla, chocolate, and/or strawberry across platforms. Ice Cream was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍩.name: Doughnut
🍩.description: A chocolate-glazed donut  or doughnut  with rainbow sprinkles. WhatsApp features a pink glaze associated with The Simpsons. May resemble the Bagel at small sizes. Doughnut was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍪.name: Cookie
🍪.description: A golden-brown chocolate chip cookie, or biscuit, though representing the baked treat more generally. Samsung, which features a pair of cookies, previously displayed this as two saltine crackers. Cookie was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🎂.name: Birthday Cake
🎂.description: A frosted cake with lit candles, as presented for a birthday celebration. The style of cake widely varies across platforms. With white frosting and strawberries, Apple and Google’s designs suggest a Japanese Christmas cake. Other vendors depict a chocolate, pink, and/or sponge cake. Birthday Cake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍰.name: Shortcake
🍰.description: A slice of strawberry shortcake, layered with whipped cream and topped with a whole strawberry. Like the Birthday Cake, may be used to represent birthday celebrations or cake in general. Shortcake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji:  Copy
🍰.aliases:
🍰 Cake
🍰 Piece Of Cake
🍰 Strawberry Shortcake

🧁.name: Cupcake
🧁.description: An individual cupcake in a liner topped with a swirl of frosting and sprinkles. The style of cupcake widely varies across platforms. The cake may be sponge or chocolate, the frosting pink or white, and the sprinkles rainbow or red. Cupcake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥧.name: Pie
🥧.description: A baked dish with a pastry crust, filled with sweet or savory ingredients. Appearance widely varies by platform. Apple depicts a whole pie in a tin, its crimped crust scored to let out steam. Google shows a slice of pumpkin pie as served at Thanksgiving, WhatsApp and Twitter a slice of cherry pie. Pie was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍫.name: Chocolate Bar
🍫.description: A block of dark chocolate, usually shown in a red foil wrapper peeled back to show squares of the candy. WhatsApp displays the wrapper in purple, a color commonly associated with Cadbury chocolate. Chocolate Bar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍬.name: Candy
🍬.description: A small piece of round, hard sugar candy, as handed out on Halloween, wrapped with two twists on its ends. Candy and wrapper color vary widely by platform. Facebook’s design resembles a classic, unwrapped red-and-white peppermint. May also be called sweets or lollies. Candy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍭.name: Lollipop
🍭.description: A colorful swirl of hard candy on a stick, called a lollipop. Color varies widely by platform: Google displays rainbow colors, Android shades of pink, and Samsung a candy-cane-colored pinwheel. "Lollipop" was the name of version 5 of Google's Android operating system. Lollipop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍮.name: Custard
🍮.description: A golden-yellow custard dessert, as a crème caramel or flan, topped with a layer of caramel. Shown on a plate, molded in a ramekin-shape and often in a pool of caramel sauce. Custard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍯.name: Honey Pot
🍯.description: A golden-yellow pot of honey, as made by bees and desired by bears. Shown with the sweet substance oozing down its sides, often with a honey dipper inside the small vessel.  May be used figuratively, as the term of endearment “honey.” Honey Pot was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍼.name: Baby Bottle
🍼.description: A bottle of milk or formula, as or fed to a baby, with a bluish cap and rubber nipple or teat. Positioned upright or at a 45° angle, and filled to various levels, sometimes showing fill lines. Often used for newborns and childrearing. See also Breast-Feeding. Baby Bottle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥛.name: Glass of Milk
🥛.description: A tall glass of white milk, as from a cow but also other mammals, nuts, or plants. Most platforms depict a glass filled near to the brim, but some show a glass half-full—or half-empty. Glass of Milk was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

☕.name: Hot Beverage
☕.description: A cup of a steaming-hot beverage, usually taken as coffee or tea. Sometimes shown on a saucer. Samsung features a foamy-white tulip latte art design. May be paired with the Frog Face to represent the snarky But That's None of My Business meme.  Hot Beverage was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.   Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍵.name: Teacup Without Handle
🍵.description: A cup of green tea, as the minty-colored Japanese matcha, usually shown on a wooden mat. Matcha is traditionally served in a small bowl that resembles a cup without a handle. Often taken as a bowl of soup, such as a split pea. Teacup Without Handle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy
🍵.aliases:
🍵 Green Tea
🍵 Matcha
🍵 Matcha Green Tea

🍶.name: Sake
🍶.description: Japanese sake, an alcoholic beverage made from rice. Shown as a sake set with a carafe  tokkuri  and drinking cup  choko . Color varies widely by platform, with Apple, WhatsApp, and Twitter featuring blue, a traditional ceramic color. Samsung displays the Japanese script for “sake” in red. Sake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Sake Bottle and Cup” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍾.name: Bottle with Popping Cork
🍾.description: A green bottle of champagne or sparkling wine with label, its cork popping to shoot out its bubbly contents. Used for a range of celebratory occasions, such as New Year's Eve, birthdays, weddings, or other life accomplishments.  Bottle with Popping Cork was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍷.name: Wine Glass
🍷.description: Red wine served in a stemmed glass. Google previously displayed an orange-colored drink that resembled cognac. Wine Glass was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍸.name: Cocktail Glass
🍸.description: A stemmed glass with a cone-shaped bowl, used for serving cocktails. Depicted as a martini garnished with an olive. Might be gin or vodka, shaken or stirred. See also Tropical Drink. Cocktail Glass was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍹.name: Tropical Drink
🍹.description: A sunset-orange-colored tropical beverage in a stemmed glass, as a rum punch or mai tai. Served with a straw and fruit garnish. Many platforms include a cocktail umbrella, hence umbrella drink. Samsung previously featured an electric-blue concoction. See also Cocktail Glass. Tropical Drink was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍺.name: Beer Mug
🍺.description: A beer, as a golden-colored lager, in a frosty mug. Depicted with a frothy head spilling over the brim. Clinking Beer Mugs is a variation that displays two such beer mugs. Beer Mug was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍻.name: Clinking Beer Mugs
🍻.description: Two frosty mugs of beer with frothy heads being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast  “Cheers!” . Several platforms include stylized lines to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Glasses. Clinking Beer Mugs was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥂.name: Clinking Glasses
🥂.description: Two flutes of champagne or sparkling wine being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast  “Cheers!” . Samsung’s design suggests two glasses of white wine. Some platforms include stylized links to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Beer Mugs—and Bottle With Popping Cork for a refill. Clinking Glasses was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥃.name: Tumbler Glass
🥃.description: A short, flat glass, as used for brown liquors like whiskey or Scotch whisky. Apple and WhatsApp serve theirs neat, while other platforms include ice  "on the rocks" . Samsung's glass features the faint initials ONI, an apparent in-company easter egg.   Tumbler Glass was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥤.name: Cup with Straw
🥤.description: A drinking cup with a straw. Depicted on many platforms as a disposable cup with a lid and bendy straw, as used to serve soft drinks at fast-food restaurants. May be used for a range of non-alcoholic beverages, including milkshakes, smoothies, juice, and to-go beverages. Color and design vary by platform. Twitter's design suggests a glass of water, Samsung displays Slightly Smiling Face on a red label. Cup with Straw was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥤 Milkshake
🥤 Smoothie
🥤 Soda Pop
🥤 Soft Drink

🧃.name: Beverage Box
🧃.description: Beverage Box was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🧉.name: Mate
🧉.description: Mate is a caffeinated beverage popular in many South American countries. Green in color  from a key ingredient: the dried leaves of yerba mate  and consumed via a metal straw. This drink is commonly referred to as yerba mate in English, and sometimes spelled maté  to distinguish from a mate, as in friend . Mate was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Mate Drink” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🧊.name: Ice
🧊.description: Ice was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Ice Cube” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in 2019. Now supported on all updated systems.

🥢.name: Chopsticks
🥢.description: A pair of equal-length chopsticks, an eating utensil used throughout East Asia. Design and color vary widely by platform, though often red or wood-colored and with tips angled together. Featured in many platforms' Steaming Bowl of Food and Takeout Box. A counterpart to utensils such as Fork and Knife and Spoon. Chopsticks was approved as part of Unicode 10.0 in 2017 and added to Emoji 5.0 in 2017. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍽.name: Fork and Knife with Plate
🍽.description: A silver fork and knife on either side of a white plate, as set for dinner or another meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon.   Fork and Knife with Plate was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🍴.name: Fork and Knife
🍴.description: A silver fork to the left of a knife, silverware or cutlery used to eat a meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon or used with Fork and Knife With Plate. Fork and Knife was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🥄.name: Spoon
🥄.description: A silver spoon, as used to eat soup, cereal, or ice cream as well as serve food or stir drinks. Positioned at various angles across platforms. May be paired with Fork and Knife, Fork and Knife With Plate, and Bowl With Spoon. Spoon was approved as part of Unicode 9.0 in 2016 and added to Emoji 3.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🏁.name: Chequered Flag
🏁.description: A flag with black and white squares shown in a checkerboard pattern, used to signal the start or end of a motor car race. Chequered Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🚩.name: Triangular Flag
🚩.description: A triangular red flag on a post. Most commonly associated with golf, as shown in the flag in hole emoji. Triangular Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Triangular Flag on Post” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🎌.name: Crossed Flags

🏳.name: White Flag
🏳.description: A white flag, shown waving on a post. Traditionally used as a sign of surrender, the meaning of this flag as an emoji is less defined. White Flag was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Waving White Flag” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🏳️\u200d🌈.name: Rainbow Flag
🏳️\u200d🌈.description: A flag with six colors of the rainbow, generally including red, orange, yellow, green, blue and purple. Commonly used by the LGBT movement as a gay pride flag, or simply pride flag and seen at Pride events. In February 2019 misinformation was spread about a so-called "anti-lgbt emoji" which can be created using a combining character to show a black and white glyph like 🚫 on top of the rainbow flag. This is possible with any emoji on supported platforms, in the same way keycaps are combining characters. The Rainbow Flag emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🏳 White Flag, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and 🌈 Rainbow. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Rainbow Flag was added to Emoji 4.0 in 2016. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy

🏳️\u200d⚧️.name: Transgender Flag
🏳️\u200d⚧️.description: A flag with horizontal pale blue and pale pink stripes with a single white stripe in the middle, used as a Transgender or Transgender Pride flag and commonly seen at Pride events. Approved in early 2020, some platforms added support while in draft status  Twitter, WhatsApp, Facebook . Coming to major operating systems by the end of 2020. The Transgender Flag emoji is a ZWJ sequence combining 🏳 White Flag, ‍ Zero Width Joiner and ⚧ Transgender Symbol. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Transgender Flag was added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020. Copy and paste this emoji: Copy 🚩 New in Emoji 13.0, coming to more platforms in the second half of 2020.
🏳️\u200d⚧️.aliases:
🏳️‍⚧️ Blue, Pink, and White Flag
🏳️‍⚧️ Trans Flag
